==English==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|*overheren}}, from {{inh|en|ang|oferhȳran}}, {{m|ang|oferhīeran||to overhear, hear, disobey, disregard, neglect}}, equivalent to {{prefix|en|over|hear}}. Cognate with {{cog|nl|overhoren||to hear, hear about}}, {{cog|de|überhören||to not hear, ignore}}, {{cog|da|overhøre||to overhear}}, {{cog|is|yfirheyra||to hear}}, {{cog|got|*𐌿𐍆𐌰𐍂𐌷𐌰𐌿𐍃𐌾𐌰𐌽|t=to disregard, disobey}} (in {{m|got|𐌿𐍆𐌰𐍂𐌷𐌰𐌿𐍃𐌴𐌹𐌽𐍃}}).

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/oʊ.vɚ.hɪɚ/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ɪə(ɹ)|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|overhears|overhearing|overheard}}

# {{lb|en|ambitransitive}} To [[hear]] something that was not meant for one's ears.
#: ''I was hanging clothes in the garden and I '''overheard''' the neighbours talking about Sheila's pregnancy.''

